  {
    "type": "EXEGETICAL (ORIGINAL LANGUAGES)",
    "name": "Pulpit Commentary",
    "elements": [
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "cmt_sub_title",
        "text": "Verse 55",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " should not have been separated from the last word of the previous verse. ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "cmt_word",
        "text": "The families of the scribes",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " is linked on by the conjunction and (which has coupled the former sons of Salma also two and two) with \"the Zorites.\" This sixth set of descendants from Salma is exhibited to us in the shape of a trio of scribe families, the heads of which will have been, presumably, ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "cmt_word",
        "text": "Tira,",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " Shimea, and ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "cmt_word",
        "text": "Suchah",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ". They are said to have ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "cmt_word",
        "text": "dwelt at Jabez",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ", a place not ascertained; and scarcely to be put into connection with the Jabez of ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "1 Chronicles 4:9",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ". The Vulgate has ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "accented",
        "text": "translated",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " the names of these three families: ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "accented",
        "text": "Canentes et resonantes et in tabernaculis commorantes",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ";\" and Bertheau advocates the interpretation. These families, it appears, were not purely of Judah; but very interesting it is that, though of the people whose land and possessions were to yield to the descendants of Abraham (",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
